      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The Bad",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "heading",
        "tag": "h3",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Similar to the first entry in the ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Octopath Traveler",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " series, each character’s plot in the sequel feels disconnected from one another. There are moments where characters engage in optional dialogue, however, even the fact that they lack voice acting makes them lack importance. There is the addition of Joint Quests that are short sub-chapters which involve two characters at once, but these feel tacked on, almost like an attempted band-aid fix. It’s clear that Square Enix wants each plot to feel personal and unique, but the obvious disengagement from the octo-party is always apparent. These moments are proved worse during the cutscenes where you only have a single character but then battle triggers and the rest of the party are there ready to fight by your side. One of the things here is while these people are in a group, the story does nothing to really give the characters a reason to party up and realistically go out of there way to help each other instead of focusing on their own problems.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Following on from the previous point, ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Octopath Traveler 2",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " can sometimes feel like a slog in which you merely progress from one checkpoint to the next. For example, when beginning a chapter, you walk into bustling new cities and fascinating locations. However, to progress, you merely follow the checkpoints, watch the chapter progress, fight when the game tells you to, and then head to the next location for another party member’s chapter. Rinse and repeat. Also, you can't swap out your first choice character until you finish their story line, so you might want to be careful with whom you pick first.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The levelling system between chapters seems wildly inconsistent. For example, when I started Temenos's third chapter, it had a recommended level of 24 and yet, in the same city, I had the option to start Ochette's second chapter, which had a recommended level of 29. Inconsistencies such as this are common throughout the majority of the game, along with a very steep difficulty spike after the first round of chapters. Many times I felt as though I was too strong, only to start another chapter and get absolutely pommeled, with no large level gaps to note.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Lastly, who was the one at Square Enix that thought they should put the Defend option next to the Flee option?! I'm not mad, just disappointed.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
